SECTION 1 — Definition and Scope of Human Ecology
Where ecology meets human society
1.1 What is Human Ecology?
Human Ecology is a branch of ecology that studies the relationships between human beings and their
natural, social, built, and cultural environments. It examines how humans depend on, interact with,
modify, and are affected by their environment — at scales ranging from an individual household to global
civilisation.
Scholar Definition
Robert Park & Ernest
Burgess (1921)
Human ecology is the study of the spatial and temporal relationships of human beings
as affected by the selective, distributive, and accommodative forces of the
environment. (Chicago School of Sociology — first formal use of the term)
Amos Hawley (1950) "Human ecology is the study of the form and development of the human community."
He emphasised organisation and adaptation.
Paul Shepard (1967) "Human ecology focuses on the interrelationships between humans and their
environments, encompassing both natural and cultural dimensions."
Moran (2008) "Human ecology examines the relationships between people, their biology, their
cultures, and their environments across time and space."
1.2 Scope of Human Ecology
Dimension What it studies
Biological dimension How human biology (genetics, physiology) is shaped by the environment
Ecological dimension How humans depend on and interact with ecosystems
Social dimension How human societies are organised in response to environmental conditions
Cultural dimension How cultural practices reflect environmental adaptations
