SECTION 2 — Key Concepts in Human Ecology
The vocabulary you must know
n Adaptation
The process by which humans adjust biologically, behaviourally, or culturally to environmental
conditions. Three types: Genetic adaptation (evolution), Physiological adaptation (acclimatisation), and
Cultural adaptation (technology, clothing, diet).
n Cultural Ecology
Study of how human cultures adapt to their natural environments. Coined by Julian Steward (1955).
Example: nomadic herding in arid zones.
n Human Niche
The total set of resources, conditions, and relationships that a human population exploits and interacts
with. Similar to ecological niche.
n Carrying Capacity for Humans
The maximum human population that can be sustained by available resources without degrading the
environment. Currently ~7.9 billion humans are testing Earth's carrying capacity.
n Anthropogenic
Caused or produced by human activity. Example: anthropogenic climate change, anthropogenic land
use change.
n Ecological Footprint
The total area of productive land and water needed to produce the resources consumed and absorb the
wastes generated by a human population. Unit: global hectares (gha). India's footprint < 2 gha/person;
USA > 8 gha/person.
n Biocultural Approach
Understanding humans as simultaneously biological organisms and cultural beings — both aspects
shape human-environment relationships.
n Subsistence Strategy
The way humans obtain food and resources — hunting-gathering, pastoralism, agriculture, industrial
production, post-industrial economy.
n Settlement Pattern
The spatial arrangement of human dwellings and communities in a landscape — dispersed, nucleated,
or linear.
n Urban Heat Island (UHI)
The phenomenon where urban areas are significantly warmer than surrounding rural areas due to
human activities and built surfaces absorbing heat.
