SECTION 3 — The POET Model of Human Ecology
Otis Duncan's classic framework (1961)
The POET model, proposed by Otis Dudley Duncan (1961), is the most famous framework in human
ecology. It identifies four key components of the human ecosystem and their interactions:
POET Model of Human Ecology (Duncan, 1961)
HUMAN
ECOSYSTEM
POPULATION
(P)
ORGANISATION
(O)
ENVIRONMENT
(E)
TECHNOLOGY
(T)
All 4 components interact with each other — change in one affects all others
Fig 2: POET Model — All four components interact bidirectionally
P —
Population
Size, density, distribution, age structure, growth rate, migration patterns of the human
population. A growing population needs more food, water, space ® pressure on
environment.
O —
Organisation
Social, political, economic, and cultural institutions through which humans organise
themselves — governments, laws, markets, families, religions. Organisation
determines how resources are distributed and how environmental decisions are made.
E —
Environment
The physical and biological surroundings — land, water, air, climate, soil, flora, fauna.
Provides resources and absorbs wastes. Human impacts on environment include
deforestation, pollution, land degradation, climate change.
T —
Technology
Tools, techniques, and knowledge that humans use to exploit the environment.
Technology mediates the relationship between population and environment. Industrial
technology increased exploitation; green technology can reduce environmental impact.
n EXAM TIP: POET model is VERY FREQUENTLY asked. Full form: Population, Organisation,
Environment, Technology. Author: Otis Dudley Duncan (1961). All 4 components are
interdependent — change in any one affects all others.
