10.1 Push Factors (Reasons to LEAVE rural areas)
• Poverty and unemployment — limited non-farm job opportunities
• Agricultural failures — drought, flood, crop failure
• Low wages in agriculture compared to industrial/service jobs
• Lack of basic services — poor schools, hospitals, roads
• Social discrimination — caste, gender, tribal issues
• Land fragmentation — subdivision of land makes farming unviable
• Natural disasters — cyclones, floods displacing communities
10.2 Pull Factors (Reasons to COME to cities)
• Employment opportunities — factories, shops, IT sector, services
• Higher wages — income several times higher than rural
• Better education — schools, colleges, coaching centres
• Healthcare — hospitals, specialists, medical facilities
• Infrastructure — electricity, water supply, internet, transport
• Social mobility — escape from rigid rural social structures
• Entertainment and culture — cinemas, malls, cultural events
10.3 Consequences of Rural-Urban Migration
For Urban Areas:
Slum growth; overcrowding; increased pressure on water, housing, transport; informal economy growth;
social diversity; labour for industries
For Rural Areas:
Brain drain (educated youth leave); ageing rural population; loss of agricultural workforce; remittance
income; reduced social cohesion
