SECTION 12 — Human-Environment Interaction Models
How different schools of thought view human-nature relationship
Environmental
Determinism
The natural environment determines human culture, society, and behaviour.
Proposed by Ellsworth Huntington and Friedrich Ratzel. Example: "People living
in harsh cold climates are hardworking because the environment forces them to
be." CRITICISED for being racist and oversimplistic. Now largely rejected.
Possibilism The environment sets limits and possibilities but humans have free will and
can choose how to respond. Proposed by Vidal de la Blache (France). Example:
A desert environment does not determine that only one culture exists — various
societies have thrived in deserts using different strategies.
Neo-determinism /
Stop and Go
Determinism
Proposed by Griffith Taylor. A middle path — the environment imposes
constraints, but technology and knowledge can help overcome them (to a
degree). "Man can alter but not abrogate nature's plans."
Systems Ecology
Approach
Humans and nature are part of the same system with feedback loops, inputs,
outputs, and thresholds. Human settlements are subsystems of larger
ecosystems. Odum's systems ecology approach.
Political Ecology Environmental problems are rooted in political and economic power
structures. Resource degradation affects the poor and marginalised most.
Combines ecology with social science analysis.
n EXAM TIP: Environmental Determinism vs Possibilism is a CLASSIC NET question. Remember:
Determinism = environment CONTROLS humans (Huntington, Ratzel); Possibilism = environment
gives OPTIONS but humans CHOOSE (Vidal de la Blache).
