SECTION 13 — Environmental Problems Linked to Human Settlement
From local to global scales
Problem Description & Data
Land Degradation Deforestation for settlements; overgrazing; soil erosion; waterlogging from irrigation;
salinisation. India loses ~5,300 MT of topsoil annually.
Water Scarcity Overextraction of groundwater for urban and agricultural use. 21 Indian cities (incl. Delhi)
face Day Zero risk by 2030 (NITI Aayog). Groundwater table falling 0.5-1m/year.
Deforestation Land cleared for agriculture, settlement, and industry. Global deforestation rate: ~10
million hectares/year. India lost ~16,000 km² of forest between 1980-2000.
Biodiversity Loss Habitat fragmentation and destruction from urban sprawl and agriculture. Currently ~1
million species face extinction (IPBES, 2019).
Climate Change Human settlements emit CO2, CH4, N2O. Urban areas produce ~70% of global GHG
emissions. Effects: sea level rise, extreme weather, food insecurity.
Waste Generation Solid waste (MSW), e-waste, industrial hazardous waste, biomedical waste. India
generates ~62 MT MSW/year; only ~22% is processed.
Air and Water Pollution 14 of the 20 most polluted cities in the world are in India. Gangetic plain villages and Delhi
face severe PM2.5 exposure.
